# GPX format

RunMapper exports valid GPX 1.1 that any tool can read, plus a custom extension block that lets us re-open the file as a fully-editable RunMapper route.

## Output structure

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<gpx xmlns="http://www.topografix.com/GPX/1/1"
     xmlns:rm="https://runmapper.app/schema/1"
     creator="RunMapper" version="1.1">
  <metadata>
    <name>{route.name}</name>
    <time>{ISO-8601}</time>
    <extensions>
      <rm:runmapper>
        <rm:profile>{trekking|...}</rm:profile>
        <rm:waypoints>
          <rm:wp id="..." index="0" lat="..." lon="..." name="..."/>
          ...
        </rm:waypoints>
        <rm:legs>
          <rm:leg fromId="..." toId="..." status="ok"
                  distanceM="..." ascentM="..." descentM="..."/>
          ...
        </rm:legs>
      </rm:runmapper>
    </extensions>
  </metadata>
  <wpt lat=".." lon=".."><name>Point 1</name></wpt>
  ...
  <trk>
    <name>{route.name}</name>
    <trkseg>
      <trkpt lat=".." lon=".."><ele>..</ele></trkpt>
      ...   <!-- concatenation of all leg coords -->
    </trkseg>
  </trk>
</gpx>
```

The `<wpt>` elements duplicate the planned waypoints so the file is meaningful in any GPX viewer. The `<trk>` polyline concatenates every leg's routed coordinates.

## Round-trip rules

- `parseGpx(xml)` first looks for `<rm:runmapper>` — if present, rebuilds waypoints/legs/profile losslessly using the extension data and slices the track between waypoint indices.
- If `<rm:runmapper>` is absent (third-party GPX) and the file has `<trkpt>` entries, simplify the track into editable control waypoints. Preserve the original GPX geometry by storing the full original trackpoint slice inside each simplified leg's `coords`, and do not call BRouter on load.
- If a third-party GPX has no `<trkpt>` entries but does have `<wpt>` entries, import those waypoints without legs.

## Generic GPX performance note

Generic GPX import must not create a marker for every trackpoint. Large activity exports can contain thousands of points and will destroy iPad performance if each becomes a waypoint/leg. Use `simplifyTrackpointIndexes()` in `src/services/gpx.ts`: exact consecutive dedupe, minimum control spacing, Douglas-Peucker simplification in meter space, and a hard editable-waypoint cap (currently 500). First and last trackpoints are always preserved.

The simplified waypoints are editing handles, not the full displayed geometry. Each imported `Leg` should contain the original GPX trackpoint segment between adjacent retained control indexes so the route line still follows the source file closely.

## Don't break

- Keep the `runmapper:` namespace at `https://runmapper.app/schema/1`. If you ever need to evolve the extension, bump to `/2` and parse both.
- `wp/@_index` is the source of truth for waypoint order in extensions. Do not rely on document order.
- Always include `<ele>` on `<trkpt>` when a leg coord has it (BRouter returns elevation per vertex). Some downstream tools (e.g. Strava import) silently drop ascent stats without it.

## Filename UX

`saveGpxAs` ensures `.gpx` extension via `ensureGpxExtension`. `parseGpx` accepts an optional file name and uses it to default the route name when GPX `<metadata><name>` is missing.
